  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1458540102" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1458540102" />
    <a title="Lisa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36425269-lisa"><img alt="Lisa" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1458540102?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa" href="/user/show/36425269-lisa">Lisa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1458540102" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3417517622174059731">This is the first book I&apos;ve ever read by Beth Harbison and while I was ultimately left a little disappointed, I did enjoy her narrative voice enough that I&apos;ll be looking for more of her books in the future.<br/><br/>When in Doubt, Add Butter started out as a great book. I liked the main character/narrator, Gemma, and thought her job as a personal chef was cool and different. There are a million books out there about cops, PIs and CEOs but I&apos;ve never read one about a personal chef before. The pace was good</span>
  <span id="freeText3417517622174059731" style="display:none">This is the first book I've ever read by Beth Harbison and while I was ultimately left a little disappointed, I did enjoy her narrative voice enough that I'll be looking for more of her books in the future.<br /><br />When in Doubt, Add Butter started out as a great book. I liked the main character/narrator, Gemma, and thought her job as a personal chef was cool and different. There are a million books out there about cops, PIs and CEOs but I've never read one about a personal chef before. The pace was good and I was happily devouring every page as we met Gemma's clients and family.....until about the halfway point. Unfortunately things kind of stalled out there and the rest of the book limped along at a much slower pace.<br /><br />There were a couple of very weak "mysteries" going on in Gemma's life and the solutions were completely telegraphed from the moment they were introduced, but our heroine remained determinedly clueless for ages and ages. That made everything feel like it dragged on as the reader hung around waiting for Gemma to finally catch a clue. Also there were a lot of different plots going on regarding Gemma's various clients and I expected them to all tie in to the over-arching plot somehow by the end. They didn't. In fact, nothing about this book was really brought to a successful conclusion. The romance that started out so steamy completely fizzled after their first encounter. The pregnant cousin was virtually irrelevant to the plot and only seemed to be there so Gemma could have some dialogue with another person instead of just herself. And her sudden dream job prospects at the end came out of nowhere and then were totally abandoned immediately after they were introduced. In short, it all kind of fell apart at the end.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />Okay so we've got Gemma a personal chef who makes a passable but not great living cooking dinner for a different rich family every night of the week. Half of her clients are cool, the other half are insanely high-maintenance. The one she likes best is "Mr. Tuesday." His real name is Paul Macknamera (or something like that) and the two of them have spent the last year leaving cute notes for each other and occasionally having sarcastically humorous phone calls but have never met in person. This was the first question mark on this book. According to Gemma's inner monologue, in order to get a new client she puts an expensive ad in a swanky magazine, then meets with the potentials to discuss their dietary needs, and finally settles on an arrangement. And yet she's never met Mr. Tuesday? How could that possibly be? How did she get him as a client? Is Harbison really asking us to believe that Gemma entered into this man's employ without ever vetting him to see if he was a serial killer luring her into a trap? And that Paul likewise hired a complete stranger, sight-unseen and gave her a key to his apartment so she could go in there completely unsupervised while he was at work?? Yeah I can't suspend my disbelief enough to buy that. It was a glaring example of plot contrivance.<br /><br />Gemma accidentally runs over a client's pet peacock and gets fired which conveniently gives her a free Friday night. She goes to a club in Mr. Tuesday's neighborhood with a friend and meets a hot guy. He introduces himself as "Mack" and they end up having a one-night stand. They use Gemma's friend's apartment just in case he turns out to be a weirdo and make use of some 10-year-old condoms in the friend's drawer for birth control. Gemma wakes up hungover the next morning and knocks a bottle of water over on the note Mack left for her. The note is ruined so she's got no idea what it said and no way to contact him.<br /><br />It was so obvious to the reader that "Mack" would turn out to be Mr. Tuesday that it got really frustrating to sit through the whole first 2/3 of the book before the big "reveal" finally happened. And while I was sitting there waiting for everyone in the book to catch up, I kept wondering why Mr. Tuesday had never noticed that his one-night stand and his chef had the same first name. Gemma isn't exactly a common name so any normal person would have said "hey that's my chef's name" when they met at the bar. It isn't until they finally do meet that we're told she never told him her name during their encounter. Again, I find this hard to believe. They spent the whole night hanging out and flirting at the bar before spending the night having sex and she never gave him even her first name?? And he never asked?? Yeah, thats just more plot contrivance. And why, if Paul/Mack/Mr. Tuesday was so interested in seeing her again, didn't he go back to the friend's apartment and ask for Gemma's number? The whole romance mystery was just one plot contrivance after another.<br /><br />Once they finally do figure out who each other are.....nothing happens. I don't think they even slept together again for the whole rest of the book. They just sort of hang out a few times and that's it. It was weird and anticlimatic after listening to Gemma fantasize about him for the majority of the book.<br /><br />Of course the big elephant in the room is that Gemma is pregnant from their brief encounter. This too took her ages to figure out when the reader knew about it right from the first bout of nausea. Once she and Mack find each other, she hesitates to tell him about the baby. I can understand why she didn't just blurt it out the first time she and Mack realized who they were, but it shouldn't have taken her as long as it did to finally spill the beans.<br /><br />Mack has just taken a job as a partner in a law firm in Seattle and will be leaving in a few weeks so that complicates things quite a bit. When Gemma starts losing clients to one crazy mishap after another I kind of figured this was setting things up so that she'd be free from career encumbrances when Mr. Tuesday finally proposed to her and thus she'd be happy moving to Seattle with him. But instead, right at the end of the book Gemma is virtually handed the executive chef job at a restaurant in D.C. and a book deal at the same time, thereby giving her a strong motivation to NOT go to Seattle. So then I thought this conflict was going to serve as the climax at the end of the book. Gemma has to decide whether to stay in D.C. and pursue her dream job, but do so as a single parent, or go with Mack. Or the reverse, that Mack has to decide whether to give up his very lucrative job. But no, that doesn't happen. Gemma has a very mild medical scare with the pregnancy and the two declare that they'll "make it work" without ever even discussing the job thing. Then the book ends and the epilogue picks up a year later with a 1-sentence blip about how Gemma just quit all her jobs in D.C. and moved to Seattle where she's very happy. Erm...okay...I guess... Why bother introducing her dream jobs in D.C. if they weren't going to play a part in the plot?<br /><br />And that feeling kind of summarizes the majority of the subplots in this book. What purpose did any of her clients serve in the over-arching plot? The crazy Russians with their arguing and psychics. Neat characters, but ultimately didn't contribute anything to the big picture. The off-the-charts anal retentive wife with the neglected husband who likes to diddle the hired help. That was interesting enough while we were reading it, but only because I thought it was going to tie in with the main plot at some point. It didn't. The morbidly obese shut-in who's trying to lose weight. Also an interesting character, but she didn't affect the plot at all either. Lex, the probably-gay client who runs a clothing store. His purpose seemed to be to facilitate her getting the dream job at the end, but since that job ultimately didn't affect the plot at all either, he was basically a waste too. The pregnant cousin served no purpose. The friend who took her to the bar totally disappeared halfway through the book and only seemed to have been included to facilitate getting her to the bar. Even Gemma's back story of having given a child up for adoption didn't really serve a purpose.<br /><br />Basically this book read like a "day in the life" story. Instead of this being a planned out plot with a central conflict supported by subplots, it was just a random cross-section of Gemma's life. A jumble of unconnected stories tied together with string. This probably would have been fine if the main plot had been more compelling. If the romance with Mr. Tuesday had been stronger, or the conflict over the baby or over whether they'd try to make a go of it as a couple had been more dramatic. Then the subplots would have been nice flavor text around the main story. But unfortunately the main plot is just weak and kind of gets buried under all the subplots.<br /><br />I also had trouble picturing Gemma. We never got a very good description of how she looked and whenever she described her clothing it was almost always ratty old sweats with food stains and no makeup or jewelry....and yet multiple people in the book refer to her as beautiful. I had trouble reconciling this.<br /><br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />All in all, this could have been a great book. The writing was smooth and I liked Gemma as a character. But it just didn't hang together.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3417517622174059731" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


